@guozhangwang as mentioned over chat. One thing i'm not 100% sure on is what to do if `hasNext` or `next` are called on the iterator post close. At the moment it behaves as if there is no next value, so `hasNext` will return `false` and `next` would throw `NoSuchElementException`.  Are we ok with this? Or should we throw an `InvalidStateStoreException`, or similar, if the iterator has been closed?

Also, has to make the `RocksDBIterator` methods `synchronized` as close can be called from the `StreamThread`

@enothereska @mjsax

@guozhangwang there was a discussion about this today. if a `Processor` writes to a `StateStore` during `init` and 0 records are processed before `StreamTask.commit()` then we throw an IllegalStateException due to the `ProcessorContext` not having a `RecordContext` set.

I think we should handle this by initially setting the `RecordContext` to a dummy record with the current wall clock time as the timestamp. 

If you are happy with this, then i'll create a JIRA for it

@jjkoshy I prefer `record.send.timeout` over `send.timeout` or `callback.timeout` because the later can be confused with `max.block.ms`. I.e., We want to avoid questions like _is send timeout measured from beginning or end of producer.send_. Secondly, this patch is about when a record times out as opposed to when send times out. 

Assuming we'll set a large default value for `record.send.timeout`, one way to set this value might be `Math.max(record.timeout.ms, linger.ms + (retries + 1) * (request.timeout.ms + retry.backoff.ms))`. Those who need success/failure notifications "quickly" after send returns, will have to set low values of both `record.timeout.ms` and `retries`. 

Thoughts?

@junrao I found it is a little difficult to tune the buffer pool size because it is for all the partitions. For example, in a bootstrap case, we may have topic **T** with a lot of data to copy and the other topics do not have much to catch up. At a certain point, what could happen is that all the 32 MB of memory is taken by topic **T** and that would be 2K batches for that topic assuming 16 KB batch size. In this case, the producer may still expire the batches even though the buffer pool is already small.

Another thing is that we actually allocate batches at `batch.size` granularity, even if the actual size of each batch is 3 KB, with default setting it will still take 16 KB from the buffer pool standpoint. So the default setting will only support 2K batches. It is usually too small for a high volume mirror maker.

So it is kind of hard to tune the buffer pool size because on one hand 32 MB may still not be small enough, but on the other hand the 32 MB is too small.

@ijuma yes correct, however 
- this still requires a malicious attacker to multiply his resources (ok, that's not hard)
- the unintentional case is not theoretical ... it just takes some unmonitored producers configured with wrong credentials (as the broken connection is not surfaced as an Exception to the thread calling `producer.send`) to really eat up some cluster capacity
